Modern cryptography is fundamentally concerned with the problem of secureprivate communication. A Secret Key Exchange is a protocol where Alice andBob, having no secret information in common to start, are able to agree on
a common secret key, conversing over a public channel. The notion of a Se-cret Key Exchange protocol was first introduced in the seminal paper of Diffieand Hellman [


 1

]. [


 1

] presented a concrete implementation of a Secret Key Ex-change protocol, dependent on a specific assumption (a variant on the discretelog), specially tailored to yield Secret Key Exchange. Secret Key Exchange isof course trivial if trapdoor permutations exist. However, there is no knownimplementation based on a weaker general assumption.

